eference as primary; manual still documented for deep dives). Added formal-measurement subsection citing `review-latest.json`.
/Users/martin/.cursor-daybook-sync/JOURNAL.md.bak.7h13:400:- daybook usefulness: 24 lessons added today, 9 lesson-tag refs in session, boot ran 11 minutes ago — all healthy.
/Users/martin/.cursor-daybook-sync/LESSONS.md:176:- 2026-04-26 [context-opt][batch-knobs] **Context-optimisation is most effective as a batched "small-knob sweep" not as one-off tweaks per sprint.** Sprint 7h-12 batch: BLOAT 4000→3000 + boot-head 50→30 + boot-tail 40→25 + journal_archive helper landed together. Each individual knob is trivially small but the cumulative effect across a session is meaningful (~30% reduction in boot/sticky bytes). Pattern: every ~5 sprints, sweep `score_latest_reply.py`, `agent_session_boot.sh`, `prompt_resume_guard.sh`, `agent_review_loop.py`, daybook archive helpers as a single batch. Cheaper than reasoning about each in isolation; lets the parent see the cumulative envelope.
/Users/martin/.cursor-daybook-sync/LESSONS.md:325:- 2026-04-26 [discipline][self-tuning] **The discipline closes the loop only when measurement runs without agent cooperation AND results inherit forward.** Sprint 7b/7c added gates that the agent must remember to call (`agent_pre_claim.sh`, `agent_session_boot.sh`). 7d adds `agent_review_loop.py` fired by the `stop` hook (no agent action) writing `~/.cursor/hooks-log/review-latest.md`, which session N+1's `agent_session_boot.sh` heads at the top of boot output (no agent action). Pattern: any review system that depends on the reviewee remembering to review will decay. Either the review is automated (telemetry → digest) AND the digest is forced into the next session's first-screen context, or the review is theatre. Both halves required.
/Users/martin/.cursor-daybook-sync/LESSONS.md:328:- 2026-04-26 [hooks][async] **`stop` hook can run informational scripts (pre-claim, review) without blocking — exit 0 immediately, write to disk, next session reads.** Previously the only hook-output surface I knew was the immediate one (sessionStart `additional_context`, beforeShellExecution `permission`). For `stop` hook, the surface is "next session reads disk" — the hook writes `review-latest.md` and `agent_session_boot.sh` heads it on next boot. This pattern unlocks: any session-end audit that wants to influence the next session. Generalises: write to a known location, have the boot wrapper read it.
/Users/martin/.cursor-daybook-sync/LESSONS.md:340:- 2026-04-26 [auto-review][sticky-alert] **Acknowledging an auto-review alert in chat is not the fix; the alert must keep injecting until the metric heals.** Sprint 7d auto-review surfaced PROSE density 18.54% > 12% threshold; agent (me) replied "re-pinning caveman" and kept writing prose. Behavioural fix proven unreliable in same reply that names the problem. Structural fix in `prompt_resume_guard.sh` (Sprint 7g): hard-severity recs (PROSE / BLOAT / ORCHESTRATION / BOOT / DAYBOOK prefixes in `review-latest.json`) inject as `user_message` on EVERY prompt until next `stop` hook's auto-review clears them. Resume-class prompts get alerts + full boot dump; non-resume prompts get alerts-only short note. No alerts → clean passthrough, zero noise. Pattern: every monitoring signal needs a "stays-on-until-cleared" injection path, not just a one-shot reminder.
/Users/martin/.cursor-daybook-sync/LESSONS.md:372:- 2026-04-26 [auto-review][post-hoc-only][closed] **Mid-session prose-density gate via `score_latest_reply.py` integrated into `agent_pre_claim.sh` closes the gap that `agent_review_loop.py` only measures at session-stop.** Sprint 7h-10 wired the scorer to read the live transcript's most-recent assistant turn, strip code fences/inline code, count prose tokens (the/a/just/...) per total words, exit non-zero ≥12% density (matches token-economy.mdc threshold) OR ≥4000 chars (`REPLY_CHAR_BLOAT`). Gate validation: first run reported "no assistant turn yet" because the scorer didn't drill into Cursor's `{role: assistant, message: {content: [{type:text, text:"..."}]}}` envelope; fixed to always check `obj["message"]` if present. Live re-run on the prior reply: density 8.45% (clean) but chars=4935 → BLOAT triggered. Density-clean ≠ short — both axes needed. Pattern: any post-hoc measurement loop also needs a pre-claim gate that reads the same live signal; the loop's job is trend, the gate's job is THIS reply.
/Users/martin/.cursor-daybook-sync/LESSONS.md:381:- 2026-04-26 [enforcement][sticky-via-prefix] **Adding a new `<PREFIX>:` to `prompt_resume_guard.sh`'s `hard_prefixes` tuple is the cheapest way to convert an advisory log entry into a sticky-until-cleared user-visible alert.** Sprint 7h-13: `pre_claim_stop.sh` now injects `PRECLAIM:` recommendations into `review-latest.json` when `agent_pre_claim.sh` exits non-zero; one-line addition `"PRECLAIM:"` to `hard_prefixes` propagates the existing fingerprint→sticky→compact-after-N machinery to the new alert class. No new state file, no new injection path, no new compaction logic. Pattern: when a new failure mode needs sticky enforcement, prefer extending the existing alert-prefix taxonomy over inventing a parallel mechanism — the cost is one tuple entry + one upstream injector that emits with the prefix. Existing taxonomy now: PROSE, BLOAT, ORCHESTRATION, BOOT, DAYBOOK, PRECLAIM.
