/Users/martin/.cursor-daybook-sync/LESSONS.md.bak:372:- 2026-04-26 [auto-review][post-hoc-only][closed] **Mid-session prose-density gate via `score_latest_reply.py` integrated into `agent_pre_claim.sh` closes the gap that `agent_review_loop.py` only measures at session-stop.** Sprint 7h-10 wired the scorer to read the live transcript's most-recent assistant turn, strip code fences/inline code, count prose tokens (the/a/just/...) per total words, exit non-zero ≥12% density (matches token-economy.mdc threshold) OR ≥4000 chars (`REPLY_CHAR_BLOAT`). Gate validation: first run reported "no assistant turn yet" because the scorer didn't drill into Cursor's `{role: assistant, message: {content: [{type:text, text:"..."}]}}` envelope; fixed to always check `obj["message"]` if present. Live re-run on the prior reply: density 8.45% (clean) but chars=4935 → BLOAT triggered. Density-clean ≠ short — both axes needed. Pattern: any post-hoc measurement loop also needs a pre-claim gate that reads the same live signal; the loop's job is trend, the gate's job is THIS reply.
/Users/martin/.cursor-daybook-sync/LESSONS.md.bak:381:- 2026-04-26 [enforcement][sticky-via-prefix] **Adding a new `<PREFIX>:` to `prompt_resume_guard.sh`'s `hard_prefixes` tuple is the cheapest way to convert an advisory log entry into a sticky-until-cleared user-visible alert.** Sprint 7h-13: `pre_claim_stop.sh` now injects `PRECLAIM:` recommendations into `review-latest.json` when `agent_pre_claim.sh` exits non-zero; one-line addition `"PRECLAIM:"` to `hard_prefixes` propagates the existing fingerprint→sticky→compact-after-N machinery to the new alert class. No new state file, no new injection path, no new compaction logic. Pattern: when a new failure mode needs sticky enforcement, prefer extending the existing alert-prefix taxonomy over inventing a parallel mechanism — the cost is one tuple entry + one upstream injector that emits with the prefix. Existing taxonomy now: PROSE, BLOAT, ORCHESTRATION, BOOT, DAYBOOK, PRECLAIM.
/Users/martin/.cursor-daybook-sync/LESSONS.md.bak:383:- 2026-04-26 [enforcement][trend-watch] **Auto-review can detect rotting-pending by reading prior archives; one-shot session metrics miss the slow-growing failure modes.** `agent_review_loop.py` `audit_daybook` now reads the prior 2 entries from `review-archive/` (cheap regex extraction of `pending_journal_items: N` from the markdown), builds a 1-3 element `pending_trend`, and the recommender fires hard `DAYBOOK:` alert when the trend is non-decreasing. Why this matters: a single session with `pending=12` looks indistinguishable from a healthy session that just happens to have queue work; three consecutive sessions with `pending` ≥ each prior is the rot signal. Pattern: per-session metric thresholds catch acute drift; cross-session trends catch chronic drift. Both axes needed — rely on either alone and the other slips.
